Here I am nearly halfway through a 30 mile bike ride about to enter a former railway tunnel that runs 0.75 miles. The tunnel was nearly pitch dark (except for the tiniest speck of light at the other end) and dripped icy cold water all throughout the entire tunnel. It was. AWESOME!

post_text:
Summer fun!!

Traveling (with all my masks and lots of hand sanitizer!) to see family and friends has been a highlight of my summer. Reggie has been a great travel buddy, too! I even made a new friend (a pony) named Starlight.

Did you know that even though there will be no Minnesota State Fair this year, you can still find food vendors popping up around the Twin Cities? And I have made a few stops and practiced social distancing by eating some delicious food in my car (fried pickles pictured here!).

I’m currently reading “Simple Abundance” each day while enjoying the beautiful Minnesota summer. Looking forward to another great year with our amazing community at LUA!

Ms. Amelia -2nd Grade Teacher

post_text:
One highlight of my summer has been camping for 5 days near Bayfield, Wisconsin by the Apostle Islands. It was fun swimming in Lake Superior, hiking, taking the ferry to Madeline Island and riding bikes around on it, as well as enjoying campfires and sleeping in the tent every night for 5 days. I got a chance to read an amazing book that I would recommend to everyone, called the Birchbark House by Louise Erdrich. When I brought it with me camping I had no idea that the story took place on Madeline Island. I actually got to read the book on a beach with Madeline Island in the distance. How cool and crazy is that? I have also been reading a lot of books from my classroom library that I have never read before. I love to read! Hope you like my pictures of my camping trip!

Charlie Daniels 5th grade teacher

post_text:
What’s on your bucket list this summer?

Ms. Dandelet checked some items off both her bucket list and personal to-do list while SOLO Camping for the first time. Although she didn't go far, camping solo was about proving her resilience (to herself) and finding some mindful time in nature. While camping she kept herself busy reading the young adult book, Refugee which she highly recommends, and practicing color meditation in her graph paper journal. Although she didn't take selfies, she did take pictures to remember her bucket-list event!

As the Minnesota Department of Education works closely with the Minnesota Department of Health to plan for the 2020-21 school year, they want to hear from families about their experience with the distance learning this spring.

This feedback is extremely valuable. This information will allow them to help families as they balance the responsibilities of work and family, while also supporting student learning.

The survey is available in English, Hmong, Somali, and Spanish.

The survey will close on June 30, 2020.

Thank you!

post_text:
#LUA Community - this is for all of us! Adults, children, teachers, students, parents, caretakers! ✨

Our emotions are contagious! ✨

Being positive doesn't mean have a smile on your face. It does mean sharing your growth mindset and knowing that we can get through uncertain times!✨ Being positive doesn't mean cheerleading. Sometimes just listening quietly to a friend can bring them the calm they need to change their perspective! ✨

Our emotions are contagious, and so is showing up for each other! ✨

We are in this together! If seeing the positive is a struggle right now, we are here for you!!✨ Reach out to our LUA team! Adults and students are both welcome! Together, we've got this!✨ #weCODE #TEAMLUA

post_text:
Hey, LUA, why is #MindsetMonday posting on a Tuesday?? ✨

A sign, perhaps that days blending together a bit?✨ This quarantine certainly changes the feel of our calendar! ✨

We want you to know that if the extension of distance learning through the end of the year has you in a bit if a whirl, YOU ARE NOT ALONE!✨

This is why "WE'VE GOT THIS" is our mindset this week! This will take a team approach, and WE are here for you! ✨ Lean in to our LUA community ✨

If you have fallen behind or need a reboot in the category of energy and perseverance, remember...

We think that a day late is better than never submitted ✨ and that done is better than perfect ✨ We are modeling this for you today! ✨

LUA - We may be small, but we are mighty! ✨We can do hard things like quarantines and distance learning✨ WE'VE GOT THIS LUA! ✨ One day at a time! We are here for you!✨

post_text:
Something will grow from all we are going through, and that “something” will be US!

“When things are uncertain, I remind my children of the constants in our lives.”

“...connecting with teachers, laughing with friends, being with family...”

“Level Up Academy is helping my kids remember that, ‘We are resilient and we are in this together!’”

“Every morning online, they meet with their teacher, and strategize their daily learning goals.”

“Then, they begin personalized distance learning.”

“Above all else, the kids are learning about resilience, flexibility, and hope.”

“Those might be some of the best lessons that Level Up Academy ever teaches them.”

“Above all else, the kids are learning about resilience, flexibility, and hope.”

“Those might be some of the best lessons that Level Up Academy ever teaches them.”

Find Connection & Hope During Uncertainty

post_text:
So many times we see success on TV, in the news, through social media, in ways that make success seem immediate, or lucky.✨

What we don't see are the endless practices of athletes and musicians, or the countless "No"s received by authors of novels and screenplays, or the "that will never work" feedback given to inventors....✨

Let's share stories of failures and getting cut from teams! Let's share the estimated hours of practice it took us to play an instrument! Let's discuss new things we are trying and the updates of how our work is progressing!✨

When our students hear countless stories of determination, and the reality of what it takes to grow toward mastery... They will be in a better place to continue - to never give up - to understand that THIS is what it takes to turn a dream into reality! ✨

We are here for you #LUA students! We look forward to hearing stories of how your persistence helped you grow!✨

#weCODE #MindsetMonday #TEAMLUA

This quote is for our students, our families, and our teachers as we begin distance learning TOGETHER today.✨

Remember families, you may create your child's schedule. The ONLY schedule to follow today and in the days to come is the one that works for YOUR family!✨

Sometimes that means pressing pause in the middle of a lesson ✨ Sometimes it means going for a walk, taking a brain break, playing a game, having quiet time, walking away ✨ You are allowed to do this. We all will need to press pause in the days ahead. ✨

Be gentle on yourselves. Lean in to our teachers. Press pause when needed. ✨
Then, continue when you are ready... You create the pace✨

We are here for you LUA!✨ We've got this!!

With love, from your LUA team!❤️

Please see the attached updated meal flyer. This flyer includes neighborhood locations as well as the link to the updated meal questionnaire. A postcard version will be mailed to all families who qualify for free or reduced-price meals to ensure they are receiving this important information.

Please Note - neighborhood locations will receive meals on Wednesdays only, beginning April 1st. Families picking up at any of these locations will receive 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches for the week. Curbside pickup at the three school locations (Willow, Birch and Oneka) remains MWF.

Home delivery is an option for those with medically-fragile children, COVID-19 diagnosis or a lack of transportation. They'll need to complete the meal questionnaire to be considered. If a student does not live within the WBLAS boundaries, they should connect with their home district.

Thank you for your patience, keep up the great work during this new reality we are all in.

post_text:
If we are intentionally trying, can we actually fail? ✨

Let's take the word FAIL as we know it (which promotes a debilitating mindset) out of education. ✨

Let's remind ourselves that NONE of us learned to ride a bike on our first try! ✨

Let's view mistakes as growth opportunities.✨

Let's view multiple attempts as perseverance! ✨

Learning is the priority when we embrace this mindset!✨

post_text:
Good morning LUA!

We are normalizing difficult at LUA. ✨

Why? Because to some children 'difficult' gives the impression that

"This is not for me." Or

"I must not belong." Or

"I'm not smart enough." Or

"This is a sign that I should stop."

We, however, know that difficult means "I will have to give my greatest effort repeatedly over time. I will have to be persistent!" ✨

Teachers will share personal stories of how they overcame something difficult with persistence. ✨

Perhaps you will consider doing this at home as well! ✨

#weCODE #keeptrying #nevergiveup #persistence

The first step in growing is believing that we can! ✨

The second step is applying effort to our attempts.✨

And then, when we struggle, we remind ourselves that "We can do hard things!" ✨ THIS keeps us going!

Learning takes place in the struggle! ✨ When we know this we are more likely to continue trying.✨

This is our mantra when we are learning at #LUA! ✨

#weCODE #MindsetMonday

post_text:
Want to be a designer of the LUA 2019-20 Yearbook?
If so…..read on!!

Students are invited to participate in creating an original yearbook cover design. Yearbook will be in full color! We love to see bright colorful artwork. You can use any appropriate medium (markers, crayons, water colors, paint, colored pencils, etc.).
Students who wish to participate need to have their submissions turned in to Mrs. Sieleni, by Wednesday, January 8, 2020.

All LUA students will have the opportunity to select their top three choices on Friday, January 10, 2020
and winners will be announced later that day!

First place winner will be on the yearbook cover as well as their art framed and proudly displayed in the front office for all to enjoy. The second place winner will be displayed on the yearbook back cover and third place winner will be included inside the yearbook as a signature page.

We invite all LUA students to enter their artwork in our Yearbook Cover Contest.

Directors serving on the Level Up Academy Board are elected by our community; eligible voters are all parents and legal guardians of current Level Up Academy students, all current Level Up Academy Board members, and all current staff of Level Up Academy. Elections will take place from May 29th, 2019 (8:00 AM) through June 6th, 2019 (3:30PM) at Level Up Academy (ballots will be in the office).

Community Member (1 to 3 years)

write in

Parent Members (1 to 3 years)

Ashley Hayes

Dennis Hastings

write in

Teacher Members (1 to 3 years)

Amber Espinosa

Joel Giese

Charles Daniels

write in

Your voice in the school board education decision-making process matters, and it starts with school board elections – it is up to all of us to vote. Voting for school board is a powerful way to support our students and community. Our students’ futures depend on it.

Vote today!

Level Up Academy requests your attendance at its Spring Fundraiser benefiting K - 8th Grade students. THIS IS AN ADULT-ONLY EVENING.

Join community members at Level Up Academy's Spring Event to raise funds for students and classrooms.

Listen to music while you enjoy appetizers with wine and beer. The event features a silent auction, live auction, raffle drawings, music, games, student art gallery, mobile STEAM lab, photos, and more!
Invite friends and family to join this fun-filled evening that benefits the education of children in the Northeast metropolitan area of the Twin Cities, MN.

The evening is an adults-only event. Cash bar will be available.

http://rmd.me/Pa5gvv5dN7r

post_text:
**DEADLINE APPROACHING**
Open Enrollment 2019-2020 School Year **

For the 2019-2020 school year, prospective students may submit Kindergarten through eighth grade Enrollment Applications starting at midnight tonight.
Please follow the link to apply.
http://apply.levelupacademy.org/.

The list below gives a general outline of the admissions process and important dates:

Tours Available – Parents may make an appointment to tour the LUA campus by calling the school office at (651) 408-5559 or emailing info@levelupacademy.org.

Open Enrollment runs January 15 to March 1, 2019 – Applications received at any time during this Open Enrollment period are likely to be offered a classroom position. If classes become filled, applications received during Open Enrollment will be placed in a lottery to determine the placement in class and order on the waiting list for any available openings.

March 02, 2019, 1:00 pm – Lottery for 2019-20 School Year.

post_text:
LUA Families!

Due to the dangerously cold temperatures, Level Up Academy will be closed Tuesday, January 29, and Wednesday, January 30. We will monitor the weather and make decisions regarding school for Thursday later this week. Stay tuned for further updates.

Our Winter Concert scheduled for this week has been rescheduled to Wednesday, February 6th.

Stay warm and safe!
